Predicting Crime in DC (2015-2019)¶

Telon Yan¶



Introduction¶

I have been interested in trying to understand crime for a while now, and especially in understanding what causes crime, to therefore try to enact better policies and other solutions to reduce crime. Additionally, a simple mapping I did in a recent assignment got me thinking about what more I could do with mapped data. Many factors like socioeconomics (in childhood, in general), life satisfaction, and drug use have been shown to affect the likelihood of individuals to commit crimes. In this project, I want to see if those trends hold for large populations, in this case, that of Washington DC. If we are unable to determine if these relationoships exist, we may still be able to answer simpler questions using other data provided to us, such as the relationships between types of crimes or general crime rate vs time, date, and location.

I got my data from DC's own Open Data Website: https://opendata.dc.gov/

Specifically:

  • https://opendata.dc.gov/datasets/DCGIS::crime-incidents-in-2015/about
  • https://opendata.dc.gov/datasets/DCGIS::crime-incidents-in-2016/about
  • https://opendata.dc.gov/datasets/DCGIS::crime-incidents-in-2017/about
  • https://opendata.dc.gov/datasets/DCGIS::crime-incidents-in-2018/about
  • https://opendata.dc.gov/datasets/DCGIS::crime-incidents-in-2019/about
  • https://opendata.dc.gov/datasets/DCGIS::acs-economic-characteristics-dc-census-tract/about

First, we will need to retrieve the relevant data, and then process it into how we desire. Above are the reported crimes datasets for years 2015-2019, as well as socioeconomic data from 2015-2019. I chose these years to analyze since they are the most recent years in which there is socioeconomic data collected. The crime datasets already come with many attributes, and I struggled to find relevant-enough datasets with life satisfaction or drug use metrics.

Data Collection¶

First and foremost, we need the crime data. Since each year's data came separately, we also need to combine them all. I also add a year reported attribute for easy use in processing later

In [167]:
# import requests
import pandas as pd 
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import folium
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression


# Data collection and curation
dc_crime_tables = []
dc_crime_df = pd.DataFrame()

years = list(range(2015,2020))

# Make one comprehensive dataframe with every crime reported over the whole time span we're looking at
for year in years:
  dc_crime_tables.append(pd.read_csv("Crime_Incidents_in_" + str(year) + ".csv"))

  dc_crime_tables[year-2015]["Year"] = year

  # verifying that all 5 years of data have the same columns, perfect
  # print(dc_crime_tables[year].head())

  dc_crime_df = pd.concat([dc_crime_df, dc_crime_tables[year-2015]])

This is somewhat interesting as the first few of these crimes committed occured much earlier than 2015. Especially with sex abuse, victims tend to not report crimes as much as victims of other crimes like theft since it may involve their private lives, create difficult social situations, and has historically been stigmatized. While we could choose to not include data reported from a different year than the one in which the sheet is on, there is still certainly crime going on unreporting, and therefore we should expect each years worth of crime reports to be missing some counts from that year. As this applies to all years, and since there are so few of these data entries, I choose to keep them in, as a stand-in for the unknown crimes being committed during each year in question.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Marking crime data on a map¶

Like in a previous project, I want to map where crimes are happening to get an initial qualitative view of things

In [174]:
map_osm = folium.Map(location=[38.907, -77.0369], zoom_start=12)

# make different marks for the time of crime and time of day
offense_type_markers = {"ARSON":"red",
                        "ASSAULT W/DANGEROUS WEAPON":"orange",
                        "BURGLARY":"purple",
                        "HOMICIDE":"black",
                        "MOTOR VEHICLE THEFT":"green",
                        "ROBBERY":"purple",
                        "SEX ABUSE":"pink",
                        "THEFT F/AUTO":"green",
                        "THEFT/OTHER":"blue"
                        }
shift_markers = {"DAY":"certificate", "EVENING":"cloud", "MIDNIGHT":"star"}


# Iterate over all the data points and mark on regular intervals
for index, crime in dc_crime_df.iterrows():
  if (index % 300 == 0):

    folium.Marker(location = [crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]], 
                  popup = crime["Time Shift"].lower() + " " + crime["Offense"].lower(), 
                  icon = folium.Icon(color=offense_type_markers[crime["Offense"]], icon=shift_markers[crime["Time Shift"]])
                  ).add_to(map_osm)

map_osm
Out[174]:
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

This map marks a pseudorandom sample of crime data data points, differentiating between the time and types of crimes, placed at the exact locations of each report, and gives us a decent inital first picture at the trends going on. The color of each marker denote the offense of the crime. The colors are:

  • Red: Arson
  • Orange: Assault with a dangerous weapon
  • Green: Motor vehicle theft or "THEFT F/AUTO" which I presume is similar
  • Blue: Other theft
  • Purple: Burglary or robbery
  • Pink: Sex abuse
  • Black: Homicide

Additionally, the icons on each marker denote the time shift at which the offense took place (bootstrap 3 icons- these were limited so I had to be creative with what could represent day evening and night):

  • Day: the certificate icon which looks somewhat like a sun
  • Evening: Cloud icon
  • Midnight: Star icon

First just looking at the positions of the markers, there is generally a lot more crime recorded near the center of DC (excluding the touristy and politically sensitive Washington Mall and surrounding areas which are generally under high security). Other areas with no crime include Rock Creek Park, the National Arboretum, and the Anacostia Naval Station.

I additionally want to look at the number of crimes and distribution of different types of crimes per year

offense_counts = []

  offense_types_order = dc_crime_df.loc[dc_crime_df['Year']==year]['Offense'].value_counts().keys()
  offense_counts.append(np.array(dc_crime_df.loc[dc_crime_df['Year']==year]['Offense'].value_counts()))

offense_counts = np.asarray(offense_counts)
# transpose the array from being indexed first by years then by offense type, to first by offense type and then by year
# I've now decided to keep offense counts as being first indexed by year to use in later code
# This structure feels more intuitive to me
#offense_counts = offense_counts.T

# to stack the bars on top of each other instead of all on each other
y_offset = np.zeros(len(years))


# Print out a table of the counts of different crimes types alongside the graph

print("\t\t\tYear:\t2015\t2016\t2017\t2018\t2019")

for offense in range(len(offense_types_order)):

  y_offset = y_offset + offense_counts.T[offense]

  
  print('{:31s} {:<7d} {:<7d} {:<7d} {:<7d} {:<7d}'.format(offense_types_order[offense],
                                                      offense_counts.T[offense][0],

More data manipulation¶

To do this, I'lll need to do some more data processing: divide the counts of crimes by population, separate by census tracts, combine the socioeceonomic data, and then see if a relationship holds between attributes

Hypothesis Testing & Insight¶

Are there relationships in the data? I first explored the original general question I had in mind: do socioeconomic factors predict crime rates? Using the new dataset I created with crime rates and other attributes by census tract, I will take a look:

In [179]:

If there were a relationship between crime rate and the socioeconomic indicators in this data set, unemployment rate, household income, and poverty rate, then these scatterplots should show it. However, in all three it looks like crime rate does not vary with respect to any of the three. We can verify this with a linear regression test, but also probably want to remove the one massive outlier: tract 10700 with a crime rate over 50%. I also remove the rows where any of these factors do not have correct data (NaN):

These still clearly show a lack of a relationship. Just to confirm, we can look at the p-values for each of these as well. The p-value represents the likelihood that the variance in crime rate due to each of these variables could occur randomly if they had no relationship. If the p-value is greater than 0.05, or 5%, and I do not reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship. If the p-value is less than 0.05, I reject the null hypothesis, meaning that there is a high likelihood that there is actually a relationship between the variables.

Crime Rate vs Median Household Income Regression p-value: 0.805
Crime Rate vs Poverty Rate Regression p-value: 0.525

For all three, the p-values are significantly larger than 0.05, showing it is highly unlikely there is a relationship. The R-squared values are also close to 0, meaning that near 0 of the variance in crime rate is explained due to variance in the variables:

As a result, I now wonder if there is more of a relationship just in violent crime. The p-values are all on the order of 10^-9 or less, meaning that the chance that you would see such variation in violent crime rate due to random chance is less than a 10^-7%, less likely than getting attacked by a shark in the US. I can therefore reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between these variables, as the data strongly supports there being a relationship between them. The r-squared values also show that about 46.8% of the variance in crime data can be attributed to variance in unemployment rate. Independently, 20.8% can be attributed to variance in median household income, and 20.5% can be attributed to variance in poverty rate.

This raises yet another question of: how co-related are these attributes? We can perform a multiregression to find out

/usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/statsmodels/tsa/tsatools.py:117: FutureWarning: In a future version of pandas all arguments of concat except for the argument 'objs' will be keyword-only
  x = pd.concat(x[::order], 1)

While the F-statistic probability is still very low (1.60e-20) showing that there is likely a relationship, the p-values for individual variables has gone up significantly and the condition number is very high (463646), meaning that there is large collinearity between economic factors. Additionally, the R^2 has only risen to 47.6%, meaning that 47.6% of the crime rate variance is attributable to these factors, not much more than just unemployment rate alone. This model is therefore unnecessary, and the rest of the variance in crime rate is likely due to other factors.

One wrinkle in this analysis that came to mind while performing it is that people are not necessarily committing crimes where they live. If for example you wanted to kill some coworkers, you would probably do that where you work, which may be somewhere completely different from where you live. Any movement of this kind is not reflected, and therefore what this is showing is not that people who live in areas with higher unemployment necessarily commit more crime, just that more crime is committed in areas with higher unemployment, whether by residents or nonresidents.
